Business Understanding section¶

Data analytics is a new field in business that has become a must in terms of backing up your business decisions with preprocessed data and predictions that are as accurate as one can make them.

The need to understand how choices can predict movies success, has driven the film industry to gather and manipulate data for business decision optimization and to get an aggregated advantage over competitors.

Unfortunately, all this work my not guarantee the success of a movie. Having establish that, this is my business understanding of this issue.

What are the Project's goals?¶

The Project's goals are to determine if the movies were a success or not

If you’re hired as a data/business analyst to predict how well a movie will perform in theaters, what kind of data would you collect?¶

The data that I would collect are:¶

Categorical data:

  • The movie title
  • The duration of the movie
  • The director's name
  • The main actor's name
  • The year in which the movie was released
  • The genre of the movie
  • Color of the movie (Black and White or Color picture)
  • Language of the movie
  • Country where the movie was made

Numerical data:

  • Number of users that gave a review
  • Number of critical reviews on imdb
  • Content rating of the movie
  • Gross earnings of the movie
  • Budget of the movie
  • IMDB rating score for the movie

What variables are highly correlated to imdb score? In this project, you will use imdb_score to measure a movie’s success.¶

To determine which variables are correlated to imdb score we need to perform a correlation analysis, but before doing that we need to understand the data that we are going to analyze. Then, we clean the data to get rid of duplicates, drop missing values, change the datatypes of the values in the dataset, etc. After cleaning our dataset, we can perform our analysis on the data and reach to several conclusions.

Next, we begin to understand our data.

Storytelling Section¶

MOVIE SUCCESS¶

1. The project's goal was to analyze the factors that determine movie success.¶

2. From the Data Understanding section we got,¶
First, I needed to understand what kind of data I was going to perform the analyze to. 

Then, I found all the data types for each of the columns in the data, a lot of those data types were wrong, and a lot of entries had missing values.
3. From the Data Preparation section we got,¶
After finding out what type of data I was dealing with and the errors in the data, I needed to clean the dataset in order to perform any statistical analysis on it.
  • First, I removed missing values from the dataset. I'm well aware that I dropped around 1,300 rows, but I wanted my data to be as clean as possible for the first analysis, maybe after performing we can do analysis to the complete dataset with errors and compare the results for further accuracy.
  • Second, I dropped the columns that do not predict the IMDB scores.
  • Third I dropped all duplicate entries in the dataset.
  • Fourth, I created a new column under the name profit to find out the most profitable movie
  • At last, I saved my clean dataset to a csv file for later use.
4. From the Business Intelligence Section we got¶
This is were the analysis of the data happens. First of all, to analyze the data I had to load the csv file I saved previously. After performing several types of analysis and data visualization techniques I learned:
  • Avatar, Jurassic World, and Titanic are the three most profitable movies
  • The most successful directors in terms of IMDB score are Frank Darabont, Francis Ford Coppola, and Christofer Nolan
  • The best movies in terms of IMDB score are Shawshank Redemption, The Godfather, and The Dark Knight
  • The top genres in terms of IMDB score are Crime|Drama, Action|Crime|Drama|Thriller, and Western
  • In average, this is how many movies were made:
  • Movies that got a IMDB score rating between 7 and 9 in average had a bigger budget than movies with lower ratings.
  • Movies with a higher IMDB score had a better gross revenue than movies with lower ratings.
  • Majority of users voted for movies that have a rating score of 5:7.
  • Movies with a duration above 100 minutes get a score of 5 or higher.
  • There is a positive linear relationship between the amount of facebook likes and the imdb score. Better ranked movies, get more facebook likes.
  • 84.29% of the movies were made in the USA. 9% from the UK. The rest from elsewhere in the world.
  • West Germany and Israel have the best average IMDB scores in the dataset

Model Evaluation and Summary of the Final Project¶

First, we built the regression model using the several different methods. The most accurate regression method is the Random Forest Regression model with an 88.54% accuracy and an MSE of 0.137.

Second, we built the classification model using different methods. The most accurate classification model for this dataset is the Random Forest Classification model with an 99.82% accuracy and an average precision of 98%.

At last, we built the Cluster Analysis using different methods. From the analysis we got that:

  • There is a positive relationship between 4 clusters in IMDB scores. This means that the most movies got a lower imdb score and a lot less movies got a higher imdb score. Which was expected, not many movies get a high imdb score.
  • Most critics for review lied either in the cluster 1 or 3. Meaning most critics that reviewed movies reviewed movies that had an IMDB Score between 4 and 8.
  • Most movies that were made were of a duration of 100 minutes or less.

Story telling of the Final Project¶

I - Regression Analysis Summary¶

From the Regression Analysis we got these takeaways:

  • The Random Forest Regression Model was the best model to accurately predict IMDB score with an R-Squared of 88.54% and and MSE of 0.137. The variables that affect IMDB score according to our model are budget, num_critic_for_reviews, movie_facebook_likes, and duration.
  • The sklearn linear model and the Statsmodel regression equations weren't accurate at all at predicting IMDB Score. Both had an accuracy of merely 20.4%. Could be due to the dropna function.

II - Classification Analysis Summary¶

From the Classification Analysis we got these takeaways:

  • The KNN Model had an accuracy of 61.50% and an average precision of 57%. Best results are with 8 K means.
  • Feature Selection using the Extra Trees Classifier Method told us that the most important variables in the dataset are movie facebook likes, number of critics for review and number of users that voted
  • The Recursive Feature Selection model told us that the most important variables are num_critic_for_reviews, duration and num_user_for_reviews
    • The Random Forest Classification Model was the most accurate model so far with an R-squared of 99.82% and an average precision of 100%

III - Clustering Analysis Summary¶

From the Clustering Analysis we got these takeaways:

  • Profile for Movies with IMDB Score less than 4:
    • Didn't have a lot of critics for review
    • Low duration
    • Low Facebook likes in general (Cast, actors,movie page)
    • Low revenue
    • Low budget
    • Low number of users that voted
  • Profile for Movies with IMDB Score between 4 and 6:
    • Some criticts review these movies
    • Some of the movies are regular duration movies(less than 90 minutes)
    • Starting Directors
    • Unknown actors, but better nonetheless
    • Consistent amount of users that voted
    • Better budget and revenues
  • Profile for movies with IMDB Score between 6 and 8:
    • Not a lot of critics review these movies. Could be only the hardest critics that critic good movies.
    • Best duration for movies (100 minutes or less)
    • Unknown directors
    • Unknown actors but people react great to them
    • Not great revenue but good budget
    • Not many users vote for these movies
  • Profile for movies with IMDB Score greater than 8:
    • A lot of critics review these movies.
    • Long duration (more than 100 minutes)
    • Best directors
    • Best actors
    • Best revenues and budget
    • High amount of users that voted
